    "\n",
    "## Section 7: ROC Curve & AUC\n",
    "\n",
    "The ROC curve is one of the most important tools for evaluating binary classifiers. It shows the trade-off between:\n",
    "- **True Positive Rate (Sensitivity)**: How many actual job offers we correctly identify\n",
    "- **False Positive Rate**: How many non-offers we incorrectly flag as offers\n",
    "\n",
    "By varying the classification threshold from 0 to 1, we trace out the entire curve.\n",
    "\n",
    "### AUC: Area Under the Curve\n",
    "\n",
    "AUC provides a single number summarizing classifier performance:\n",
    "- **AUC = 1.0**: Perfect classifier (100% TPR, 0% FPR)\n",
    "- **AUC = 0.5**: Random guessing (diagonal line)\n",
    "- **AUC < 0.5**: Worse than random (model is inverted)\n",
    "- **AUC > 0.8**: Good classifier\n",
    "\n",
    "**Interpretation:** AUC represents the probability that a randomly chosen positive instance (job offer) will be ranked higher than a randomly chosen negative instance (no offer)."
   ]
