    "---\n",
    "\n",
    "## Summary: Key Takeaways\n",
    "\n",
    "### 1. When to Use Logistic Regression\n",
    "- **Binary outcome** (yes/no, 0/1, success/failure)\n",
    "- **OLS would give predictions outside [0,1]** - nonsensical for probabilities\n",
    "- Examples: loan default, bankruptcy prediction, customer churn, credit approval\n",
    "\n",
    "### 2. Understanding Coefficients\n",
    "- Coefficients are in **log-odds** - hard to interpret directly\n",
    "- Convert to **odds ratios** by exponentiating: $OR = \\exp(\\beta)$\n",
    "- **OR > 1**: Variable increases odds of the outcome\n",
    "- **OR < 1**: Variable decreases odds of the outcome\n",
    "\n",
    "### 3. Model Evaluation\n",
    "- **Confusion Matrix**: Shows true/false positives and negatives\n",
    "- **Accuracy**: Overall correct predictions = (TP + TN) / Total\n",
    "- **Sensitivity (Recall)**: TP / (TP + FN) - ability to detect positives\n",
    "- **Specificity**: TN / (TN + FP) - ability to detect negatives\n",
    "\n",
    "### 4. ROC Curve and AUC\n",
    "- **ROC Curve**: Trade-off between sensitivity and specificity at different thresholds\n",
    "- **AUC**: Area Under the Curve - single number summarizing discrimination ability\n",
    "  - **1.0** = Perfect\n",
    "  - **0.5** = Random guessing\n",
    "  - **>0.8** = Good classifier\n",
    "\n",
    "### 5. Classification Threshold Matters\n",
    "- Default is 0.5, but **optimal threshold varies**\n",
    "- Depends on the **relative cost** of false positives vs. false negatives\n",
    "- In credit risk: Missing a defaulter (FN) may be costlier than rejecting a good borrower (FP)"
   ]
